Full disclosure, my mental health has been in the bin so if I was doing this gig again, there‚Äôs A LOT I would do differently. I don‚Äôt feel I promoted it in the usual way I do and that likely contributed to attendance being so low. Certainly not the bands. They were mint!

So I‚Äôve given you two scenarios. The one which actually happened and what would happen if I didn‚Äôt bother paying bands, covering their food and got volunteers to work my gigs. Big difference as you can see! But one means I can sleep at night, one doesn‚Äôt.

I do have an additional cost because I‚Äôm VAT registered and many of the bands/businesses I work with aren‚Äôt so I can‚Äôt claim VAT back on a lot of things. That sucks I‚Äôm not going to lie. 20% is a lot to layout!
A lot of events are financed by relying purely on ticket sales and that‚Äôs where you end up with nervous promoters pulling gigs because they know they will lose money. I don‚Äôt work that way.
I always cost out a gig, make sure I have enough funds to cover it even if not one ticket is sold and THEN announce the gig. I then hope that ticket sales will make that outlay back for me.

Then I opened Potion at Afflecks and a combination of the pandemic, Brexit, the war in Ukraine and a cost of living crisis have battered them both. But I‚Äôm not giving up. The plan is for them both to fund themselves and the gigs I put on.
